1	\chapter{The relative Picard functor}
2	\label{chap:Picard_Functor}
3	
4	This chapter sets up Phase~C step~2: the \emph{relative Picard functor} of a curve $C$ over $\Spec k$, packaged as a contravariant functor on schemes, and the (deferred) representability theorem whose closure delivers the Picard scheme. It is the natural successor to Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}.
5	
6	The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every definition and lemma here is auxiliary, supporting the construction of $\Jac(C)$ in Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian}.
7	
8	\section{Definition}
9	
10	\begin{definition}\leanok
11	[Relative Picard functor]
12	  \label{def:Pic_functor}
13	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctor}
14	  Let $C$ be a scheme over $\Spec k$. The \emph{relative Picard functor} of $C$ over $k$ is the contravariant functor
15	  \[
16	    \PicardFunctor\, C \;\colon\; \mathrm{Sch}_k^{\mathrm{op}} \;\longrightarrow\; \mathrm{Set},\qquad
17	    S \;\longmapsto\; \Pic(C \times_k S) \,\big/\, p_S^* \Pic(S),
18	  \]
19	  where $p_S \colon C \times_k S \to S$ is the projection and the quotient is by the subgroup $p_S^*\Pic(S) \subseteq \Pic(C \times_k S)$ pulled back from $S$. Functoriality in $S$ is via base change of the fiber product and the pull-back homomorphism on Picard groups (Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback}).
20	\end{definition}
21	
22	\begin{remark}
23	  The presheaf $\PicardFunctor$ above is sometimes called the \emph{absolute} Picard presheaf; the standard \emph{relative Picard functor} of $C/k$ is its \'etale-sheafification, denoted $\underline{\Pic}_{C/k}$. For a smooth proper geometrically connected curve $C$ over a field $k$, \'etale sheafification is automatic on schemes that are themselves Picard sheaves over $S$ (the obstruction is the Brauer group), so this chapter records the presheaf definition; the \'etale sheafification is deferred to a subsequent iteration (Phase~C step~3).
24	\end{remark}
25	
26	\section{Representability}
27	
28	\begin{theorem}\leanok
29	[Representability of the Picard functor --- Grothendieck FGA, Mumford \emph{Abelian Varieties} \S III.13]
30	  \label{thm:Pic_representable}
31	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctor.representable}
32	  \uses{def:Pic_functor}
33	  Let $C$ be a smooth proper geometrically irreducible curve over a field $k$. Then $\PicardFunctor\, C$ (after \'etale sheafification) is representable by a smooth, locally finite-type group scheme $\Pic_{C/k}$ over $k$. Its connected component of the identity $\Pic^0_{C/k}$ is a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme over $k$ of dimension $g = g(C)$, hence an abelian variety.
34	\end{theorem}
35	
36	\begin{proof}
37	  \uses{def:Pic_functor, def:Scheme_LineBundle, thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback, thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}
38	  See \emph{Fundamental Algebraic Geometry: Grothendieck's FGA Explained} (Fantechi--G\"ottsche--Illusie--Kleiman--Nitsure--Vistoli, 2005), Chapter~9, and Mumford, \emph{Abelian Varieties}, Chapter~III \S13. The classical proof goes via Hilbert schemes and quotient stacks. Mathlib does not yet have the surrounding infrastructure (Hilbert schemes, quotients of schemes by finite group actions, FGA representability for moduli functors), so closing this theorem is a multi-iteration Mathlib-gap-fill task. The path adopted in this project (re-opened in iteration~076) decomposes the work into four steps (see \texttt{STRATEGY.md} Phase~C):
39	  \begin{enumerate}
40	    \item \emph{Step~C0} --- supply the symmetric monoidal structure on $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ (Chapter~\ref{chap:Modules_Monoidal}, Theorem~\ref{thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}).
41	    \item \emph{Step~C1} --- refine $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X$ (Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}) from the global-sections approximation to ``invertible $\mathcal O_X$-module''.
42	    \item \emph{Step~C2} --- re-derive $\mathrm{Pic.pullback}$, $\PicardFunctor$, and the \'etale sheafification against the refined $\mathrm{LineBundle}$.
43	    \item \emph{Step~C3} --- construct $\Pic_{C/k}$ (representing scheme) and identify its identity component $\Pic^0_{C/k}$ with $\Jac(C)$. Two routes are viable: (a) the FGA route via a Hilbert/Quot detour (Mathlib-PR-sized); (b) the symmetric-power route via $\mathrm{Sym}^g C$, requiring a project-local quotient-by-finite-group construction. The route is chosen during step~C2.
44	  \end{enumerate}
45	  Until steps~C0--C3 are complete, the Lean-side sorry remains; downstream consumers (Definition~\ref{def:Jacobian} and the four Jacobian instances of Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian}) record their dependence on it through the bundled hypothesis \texttt{nonempty\_jacobianWitness}.
46	\end{proof}
47	
48	\section{Use in the project}
49	
50	Theorem~\ref{thm:Pic_representable} is the bundled blocker for the four Jacobian.lean sorries:
51	
52	\begin{itemize}
53	  \item Definition~\ref{def:Jacobian} ($\Jac(C) = \Pic^0_{C/k}$) takes the connected component of identity of the representing scheme.
54	  \item Theorem~\ref{thm:Jacobian_grpObj} (group-object structure) is the abelian-variety structure on $\Pic^0_{C/k}$.
55	  \item Theorem~\ref{thm:Jacobian_smooth_genus} (smooth of relative dimension $g$) is the dimension formula in the representability statement.
56	  \item Theorem~\ref{thm:Jacobian_proper} (properness) and Theorem~\ref{thm:Jacobian_geomIrred} (geometric irreducibility) are direct consequences of the representability conclusion.
57	\end{itemize}
58	
59	\section{Mathlib gap}
60	
61	Mathlib has the constituent infrastructure for the \emph{definition} (Definition~\ref{def:Pic_functor}):
62	\begin{itemize}
63	  \item Fiber products of schemes.
64	  \item Line bundles and Picard groups (this project, Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}).
65	  \item Pull-back of line bundles (this project, Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}).
66	  \item Quotient groups for group quotients.
67	  \item Functor machinery for assembling the contravariant functor.
68	\end{itemize}
69	
70	What is \emph{missing} and supplied by this chapter (as a deferred sorry):
71	\begin{itemize}
72	  \item The actual representability theorem (Theorem~\ref{thm:Pic_representable}). FGA-level, kept as a sorry; all four Jacobian.lean sorries reduce to it once it is closed.
73	\end{itemize}
74	
75	\subsection{Forward-compatibility note (LineBundle approximation)}
76	
77	Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle} defines line bundles via a global-sections approximation, correct on affine schemes but a strict subgroup of the true $\Pic(X)$ on non-affine schemes. The \emph{definition} of $\PicardFunctor C$ therefore inherits this approximation: the values $\PicardFunctor(S)$ for non-affine $S$ are smaller subgroups of the true relative Picard group. Consequently the representability theorem stated above will be honest only after the line bundle definition is refined to the bespoke ``invertible quasi-coherent sheaf'' definition (gated on monoidal-category infrastructure for $\mathcal O_X$-modules, currently absent). Until that refinement lands, the representable sorry of this chapter must remain unattacked: closing it on the approximate definition would silently assert representability of the wrong functor.
78

1	\chapter{Line bundles on schemes and the Picard group}
2	\label{chap:Picard_LineBundle}
3	
4	This chapter sets up the foundational Phase~B/C infrastructure: the type of \emph{line bundles} (invertible quasi-coherent sheaves) on a scheme $X$, the abelian-group structure under tensor product, and the pull-back functoriality. It is the smallest self-contained step toward the Picard scheme construction (Theorem~\ref{thm:Pic_representable}) and feeds the Jacobian gap chain.
5	
6	The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every definition and lemma here is auxiliary, supporting the construction of $\Pic_{C/k}$ in later phases.
7	
8	\section{Definition}
9	
10	\begin{definition}\leanok
11	[Line bundle on a scheme]
12	  \label{def:Scheme_LineBundle}
13	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.LineBundle}
14	  Let $X$ be a scheme. A \emph{line bundle} on $X$ is an invertible quasi-coherent $\mathcal O_X$-module: a sheaf $L$ of $\mathcal O_X$-modules that is quasi-coherent and locally free of rank $1$. Equivalently: an object of the category of $\mathcal O_X$-modules that is invertible with respect to the tensor product $- \otimes_{\mathcal O_X} -$ in the symmetric monoidal category of $\mathcal O_X$-modules.
15	\end{definition}
16	
17	\paragraph{Status note (Phase C1, post-refactor).}
18	Following the Phase~C1 refactor (iter-109), the Lean body of \texttt{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.LineBundle} matches the geometric definition stated above. Concretely,
19	\[
20	  \mathrm{LineBundle}\,X \;:=\; \bigl(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,X.\mathrm{Modules}\bigr)^{\!\times},
21	\]
22	the units of the (commutative) monoid structure on the skeleton of the symmetric monoidal category $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ (Theorem~\ref{thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}). This mirrors the ring-side precedent $\mathrm{CommRing.Pic}\,R = \mathrm{Shrink}\bigl(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,(\mathrm{SemimoduleCat}\,R)\bigr)^{\!\times}$ at \texttt{Mathlib.RingTheory.PicardGroup:407}; the commutative-group structure derives from $\mathrm{Skeleton.instCommMonoid}$ (\texttt{Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Monoidal.Skeleton:80}) followed by $\mathrm{instCommGroupUnits}$. No \texttt{Shrink} wrapper is needed: $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ already lives in $\mathrm{Type}\,(u+1)$, so $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X$ inhabits the same universe and the downstream \texttt{PicardFunctor}/\texttt{PicardFunctorAb} codomains have been bumped to match.
23	
24	\paragraph{Load-bearing transitive dependency on the monoidality of sheafification.}
25	The $\mathrm{BraidedCategory}\,(X.\mathrm{Modules})$ instance underlying the commutative-group structure is supplied by $\mathrm{Localization.Monoidal.Braided}$ (\texttt{Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Localization.Monoidal.Braided:118}), which requires $W(X).\mathrm{IsMonoidal}$ for the sheafification class $W(X)$. This is the project's named-deferred sorry $\mathrm{instIsMonoidal\_W}$ (\texttt{AlgebraicJacobian/Modules/Monoidal.lean:166}); see the load-bearing-disclosure paragraph in Chapter~\ref{chap:Modules_Monoidal}. Post-C1, every theorem about $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X$, $\Pic(X)$, $\mathrm{Pic.pullback}$, $\mathrm{PicardFunctor}$, $\mathrm{PicardFunctorAb}$, and the downstream Jacobian arc transitively consumes $\mathrm{instIsMonoidal\_W}$; \texttt{lean\_verify} surfaces \texttt{sorryAx} in their axiom chains.
26	
27	\paragraph{Pull-back gap.}
28	Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback} below (and the associated functoriality lemmas $\mathrm{Pic.pullback\_id}$, $\mathrm{Pic.pullback\_comp}$) is currently sorry-bodied. The obstruction is a separate named-deferred Mathlib gap, recorded as Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj} below, asserting that the categorical pull-back functor $\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f$ is monoidal. The named-deferral route is chosen per analogist option~(c) of \texttt{analogies/c1-route.md}; see also the Phase~C1 row of \texttt{STRATEGY.md}.
29	
30	\begin{remark}
31	  Mathlib has the category of $\mathcal O_X$-modules and the quasi-coherence typeclass. The combination ``invertible quasi-coherent sheaf'' is not pre-packaged; it is the content of this definition.
32	\end{remark}
33	
34	\section{Group structure under tensor product}
35	
36	% NOTE: post-C1 — the Lean body of `instCommGroupLineBundle` is `inferInstanceAs (CommGroup (Skeleton X.Modules)ˣ)` (no direct `sorry`), but the `CommGroup` instance transitively consumes `instIsMonoidal_W` (Chapter~\ref{chap:Modules_Monoidal}); see the load-bearing-disclosure paragraph above.
37	\begin{theorem}\leanok
38	[Picard group of a scheme]
39	  \label{thm:Scheme_Pic_commGroup}
40	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.instCommGroupLineBundle}
41	  For every scheme $X$, the type of line bundles on $X$ (modulo isomorphism) carries a canonical commutative-group structure. The operation is tensor product over $\mathcal O_X$, the unit is the structure sheaf $\mathcal O_X$ itself, and the inverse of a line bundle $L$ is its $\mathcal O_X$-dual $L^\vee = \mathcal{H}om_{\mathcal O_X}(L, \mathcal O_X)$.
42	
43	  We denote this group by $\Pic(X)$ and call it the \emph{Picard group} of $X$.
44	\end{theorem}
45	
46	\begin{proof}
47	  \uses{def:Scheme_LineBundle, thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}
48	  \leanok
49	  Identifying $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X$ with $\bigl(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,X.\mathrm{Modules}\bigr)^{\!\times}$ (the post-refactor body), the commutative-group structure is obtained by Lean's typeclass-resolution chain
50	  \[
51	    \mathrm{BraidedCategory}\,(X.\mathrm{Modules})
52	    \;\Longrightarrow\;
53	    \mathrm{CommMonoid}\,(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,X.\mathrm{Modules})
54	    \;\Longrightarrow\;
55	    \mathrm{CommGroup}\,\bigl(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,X.\mathrm{Modules}\bigr)^{\!\times},
56	  \]
57	  via $\mathrm{Skeleton.instCommMonoid}$ (\texttt{Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Monoidal.Skeleton:80}) followed by $\mathrm{instCommGroupUnits}$. The mathematical content "tensor product of invertible quasi-coherent sheaves is invertible quasi-coherent, with $\mathcal O_X$ as unit and the $\mathcal O_X$-dual as inverse" is packaged into $\mathrm{Skeleton.instCommMonoid}$ together with the localised-monoidal infrastructure on $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ (Theorem~\ref{thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}); commutativity and associativity descend from the symmetric-monoidal structure on $X.\mathrm{Modules}$.
58	\end{proof}
59	
60	\section{Pull-back functoriality}
61	
62	% NOTE: post-C1 — the Lean bodies of `Pic.pullback`, `Pic.pullback_id`, and `Pic.pullback_comp` are currently `sorry`, blocked on Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj} (a named-deferred Mathlib gap on the monoidality of the categorical pull-back functor on quasi-coherent $\mathcal O$-modules). The named-deferral route is analogist option~(c) of \texttt{analogies/c1-route.md}. `\leanok` on the statement block certifies that the declaration is well-formed and type-checks; closure of the proof body awaits Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj}.
63	\begin{theorem}\leanok
64	[Pull-back of line bundles]
65	  \label{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback}
66	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Pic.pullback}
67	  Let $f \colon X \to Y$ be a morphism of schemes. The categorical pull-back functor $\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f \colon Y.\mathrm{Modules} \to X.\mathrm{Modules}$ induces a group homomorphism
68	  \[
69	    f^* \colon \Pic(Y) \;\to\; \Pic(X)
70	  \]
71	  by passing to invertible objects of the skeleton. Pull-back is contravariantly functorial: $(\mathrm{id}_X)^* = \mathrm{id}_{\Pic(X)}$ and $(f \circ g)^* = g^* \circ f^*$.
72	\end{theorem}
73	
74	\begin{proof}
75	  \uses{thm:Scheme_Pic_commGroup, thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj}
76	  The eventual Lean definition is
77	  \[
78	    f^* \;=\; \mathrm{Units.map}\bigl(\mathrm{Skeleton.monoidHom}\,(\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f)\bigr),
79	  \]
80	  i.e.\ the units functor applied to the monoid homomorphism on skeletons induced by a monoidal functor (\texttt{Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Monoidal.Skeleton:111}). To form $\mathrm{Skeleton.monoidHom}$ on the categorical pull-back requires a $\mathrm{Functor.Monoidal}$ instance on $\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f$, which Mathlib b80f227 does not register. The project surfaces the missing iso as the named-deferred Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj} below. Once that iso is in hand the monoidality of the pull-back is mechanical: associativity and unit coherence reduce to standard sheaf-pullback functoriality, and $f^*$ on $\Pic$ is then the composite $\mathrm{Units.map} \circ \mathrm{Skeleton.monoidHom}$ applied to the resulting monoidal-functor structure. Pending closure (or a hand-construction equivalent) of Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj}, the Lean bodies of $\mathrm{Pic.pullback}$, $\mathrm{Pic.pullback\_id}$, and $\mathrm{Pic.pullback\_comp}$ remain \texttt{sorry}.
81	\end{proof}
82	
83	\section{Monoidality of the categorical pull-back functor (Mathlib gap)}
84	
85	% NOTE: post-C1 named-deferred Mathlib gap. The Lean body is `sorry`; `\leanok` on the statement block reflects only well-formedness of the introduced declaration. Closure awaits either a Mathlib refresh landing `(SheafOfModules.pullback _).Monoidal` or a hand-construction of the tensor-preservation iso.
86	\begin{theorem}\leanok
87	[Pull-back of $\mathcal O$-modules preserves tensor product]
88	  \label{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj}
89	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.SheafOfModules.pullback_tensorObj}
90	  \uses{def:Modules_tensorObj}
91	  Let $f \colon X \to Y$ be a morphism of schemes and $M, N \in Y.\mathrm{Modules}$. Then the categorical pull-back functor $f^* := \mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f$ preserves tensor products: there is a natural isomorphism
92	  \[
93	    f^*\bigl(M \otimes_{\mathcal O_Y} N\bigr) \;\cong\; f^* M \;\otimes_{\mathcal O_X}\; f^* N.
94	  \]
95	\end{theorem}
96	
97	\begin{proof}
98	  \uses{def:Modules_tensorObj, thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}
99	  This is the standard assertion that the inverse-image functor on $\mathcal O$-modules is monoidal. Mathlib provides $\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f$ as a functor on quasi-coherent $\mathcal O$-modules and has the corresponding statement on the presheaf side, but \texttt{b80f227} does not register a $\mathrm{Functor.Monoidal}\,(\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f)$ instance. The proof proceeds by the tensor-hom adjunction together with the fact that the pull-back of the structure-sheaf-unit map is again a unit map; see Stacks~\texttt{01AC} and \S5 of Hartshorne~II for the affine-local picture. A future Mathlib refresh that lands $(\mathrm{SheafOfModules.pullback}\,\_).\mathrm{Monoidal}$ collapses this obligation to the canonical $\mathrm{MonoidalCategoryStruct.tensorObj}$-comparison.
100	\end{proof}
101	
102	\section{Use in the project}
103	
104	The Picard group $\Pic(X)$ is the underlying \emph{set} (modulo isomorphism) of the Picard \emph{scheme} $\Pic_{C/k}$ in the curve case; the scheme structure adds a $k$-scheme of finite type representing the relative Picard functor $S \mapsto \Pic(C \times_k S) / \Pic(S)$.
105	
106	This chapter is therefore the gateway to:
107	\begin{itemize}
108	  \item Definition~\ref{def:Pic_functor} (Picard functor of $C/k$) --- quotient by $\Pic(S)$ uses Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback}.
109	  \item Theorem~\ref{thm:Pic_representable} (representability of the Picard scheme) --- uses the full $\Pic$ machinery built here.
110	  \item Definition~\ref{def:ofCurve} (Abel--Jacobi map) --- defined via the line bundle $\mathcal O_{C \times C}(\Delta - p_1^* P)$ on $C \times C$, an explicit element of $\Pic(C \times C)$.
111	\end{itemize}
112	
113	Post-C1, all of these downstream consumers transitively depend on $\mathrm{instIsMonoidal\_W}$ via the $\mathrm{CommGroup}$ instance on $\Pic(X)$ (load-bearing for $\mathrm{LineBundle}$, $\Pic$, $\mathrm{Pic.pullback}$, $\mathrm{PicardFunctor}$, $\mathrm{PicardFunctorAb}$, and the Jacobian framework); the $\mathrm{Pic.pullback}$ arc additionally depends on Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj}. Both dependencies surface in \texttt{lean\_verify}'s axiom chain.
114	
115	\section{Mathlib gap}
116	
117	Mathlib has:
118	\begin{itemize}
119	  \item The abelian category of sheaves of $\mathcal O_X$-modules on a scheme $X$, together with the (presheaf-side) symmetric monoidal structure and the sheafification machinery.
120	  \item Quasi-coherence as data on a sheaf of modules.
121	  \item The skeleton-of-a-monoidal-category construction $\mathrm{Skeleton}\,C$ and the chain $\mathrm{BraidedCategory}\,C \Longrightarrow \mathrm{CommMonoid}\,(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,C) \Longrightarrow \mathrm{CommGroup}\,(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,C)^{\!\times}$ (\texttt{Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Monoidal.Skeleton}).
122	  \item The ring-side precedent $\mathrm{CommRing.Pic}\,R = \mathrm{Shrink}\,(\mathrm{Skeleton}\,(\mathrm{SemimoduleCat}\,R))^{\!\times}$ (\texttt{Mathlib.RingTheory.PicardGroup:407}).
123	  \item The categorical pull-back functor $\mathrm{Scheme.Modules.pullback}\,f$ on quasi-coherent $\mathcal O$-modules (\texttt{Mathlib.AlgebraicGeometry.Modules.Sheaf}).
124	\end{itemize}
125	
126	What is missing and supplied by this chapter:
127	\begin{itemize}
128	  \item The scheme-side $\mathrm{CommGroup}\,(\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X)$ instance, threading the skeleton-units idiom through $X.\mathrm{Modules}$. Transitively load-bearing on $\mathrm{instIsMonoidal\_W}$ (Chapter~\ref{chap:Modules_Monoidal}) for the required $\mathrm{BraidedCategory}\,(X.\mathrm{Modules})$.
129	  \item A scheme-morphism-functorial pull-back homomorphism $\Pic(Y) \to \Pic(X)$, currently sorry-bodied (Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback}).
130	  \item The monoidality iso $f^*(M \otimes N) \cong f^* M \otimes f^* N$ for the categorical pull-back on $\mathcal O$-modules, recorded as the named-deferred Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj}. Mathlib b80f227 has the analogous monoidality on the presheaf-side pushforward (\texttt{PresheafOfModules.PushforwardZeroMonoidal}) but no $\mathrm{Functor.Monoidal}$ instance for the pull-back of sheaves of modules.
131	\end{itemize}
132	
133	These are mapped to Phase~B/C step~1 of the project strategy. See also the cross-referenced load-bearing-disclosure paragraph in Chapter~\ref{chap:Modules_Monoidal} on $\mathrm{instIsMonoidal\_W}$.
