1	\chapter{The relative Picard functor}
2	\label{chap:Picard_Functor}
3	
4	This chapter sets up Phase~C step~2: the \emph{relative Picard functor} of a curve $C$ over $\Spec k$, packaged as a contravariant functor on schemes, and the (deferred) representability theorem whose closure delivers the Picard scheme. It is the natural successor to Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}.
5	
6	The chapter introduces no protected declarations: every definition and lemma here is auxiliary, supporting the construction of $\Jac(C)$ in Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian}.
7	
8	\section{Definition}
9	
10	% NOTE: post-C1 (iter-109) --- the Lean body of `PicardFunctor` is filled, but it transitively consumes the sorry-bodied $\mathrm{Pic.pullback}$ (\texttt{AlgebraicJacobian/Picard/LineBundle.lean:93}) through the quotient $p_S^*\Pic(S)$, hence transitively the named-deferred Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj} (\texttt{Picard/LineBundle.lean:82}) and $\mathrm{instIsMonoidal\_W}$ (\texttt{Modules/Monoidal.lean:166}). `\leanok` on the statement block certifies that the declaration is well-formed and type-checks; the full chain of dependencies is laid out in §"Post-C1 dependency note" below.
11	\begin{definition}\leanok
12	[Relative Picard functor]
13	  \label{def:Pic_functor}
14	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctor}
15	  Let $C$ be a scheme over $\Spec k$. The \emph{relative Picard functor} of $C$ over $k$ is the contravariant functor
16	  \[
17	    \PicardFunctor\, C \;\colon\; \mathrm{Sch}_k^{\mathrm{op}} \;\longrightarrow\; \mathrm{Set},\qquad
18	    S \;\longmapsto\; \Pic(C \times_k S) \,\big/\, p_S^* \Pic(S),
19	  \]
20	  where $p_S \colon C \times_k S \to S$ is the projection and the quotient is by the subgroup $p_S^*\Pic(S) \subseteq \Pic(C \times_k S)$ pulled back from $S$. Functoriality in $S$ is via base change of the fiber product and the pull-back homomorphism on Picard groups (Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback}).
21	\end{definition}
22	
23	\begin{remark}
24	  The presheaf $\PicardFunctor$ above is sometimes called the \emph{absolute} Picard presheaf; the standard \emph{relative Picard functor} of $C/k$ is its \'etale-sheafification, denoted $\underline{\Pic}_{C/k}$. For a smooth proper geometrically connected curve $C$ over a field $k$, \'etale sheafification is automatic on schemes that are themselves Picard sheaves over $S$ (the obstruction is the Brauer group), so this chapter records the presheaf definition; the \'etale sheafification is deferred to a subsequent iteration (Phase~C step~3).
25	\end{remark}
26	
27	\section{Representability}
28	
29	\begin{theorem}\leanok
30	[Representability of the Picard functor --- Grothendieck FGA, Mumford \emph{Abelian Varieties} \S III.13]
31	  \label{thm:Pic_representable}
32	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.PicardFunctor.representable}
33	  \uses{def:Pic_functor}
34	  Let $C$ be a smooth proper geometrically irreducible curve over a field $k$. Then $\PicardFunctor\, C$ (after \'etale sheafification) is representable by a smooth, locally finite-type group scheme $\Pic_{C/k}$ over $k$. Its connected component of the identity $\Pic^0_{C/k}$ is a smooth proper geometrically irreducible group scheme over $k$ of dimension $g = g(C)$, hence an abelian variety.
35	\end{theorem}
36	
37	\begin{proof}
38	  \uses{def:Pic_functor, def:Scheme_LineBundle, thm:Scheme_Pic_pullback, thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}
39	  See \emph{Fundamental Algebraic Geometry: Grothendieck's FGA Explained} (Fantechi--G\"ottsche--Illusie--Kleiman--Nitsure--Vistoli, 2005), Chapter~9, and Mumford, \emph{Abelian Varieties}, Chapter~III \S13. The classical proof goes via Hilbert schemes and quotient stacks. Mathlib does not yet have the surrounding infrastructure (Hilbert schemes, quotients of schemes by finite group actions, FGA representability for moduli functors), so closing this theorem is a multi-iteration Mathlib-gap-fill task. The path adopted in this project (re-opened in iteration~076) decomposes the work into four steps (see \texttt{STRATEGY.md} Phase~C):
40	  \begin{enumerate}
41	    \item \emph{Step~C0} --- supply the symmetric monoidal structure on $X.\mathrm{Modules}$ (Chapter~\ref{chap:Modules_Monoidal}, Theorem~\ref{thm:Modules_MonoidalCategory}).
42	    \item \emph{Step~C1} --- refine $\mathrm{LineBundle}\,X$ (Chapter~\ref{chap:Picard_LineBundle}) from the global-sections approximation to ``invertible $\mathcal O_X$-module''.
43	    \item \emph{Step~C2} --- close (or hand-construct an equivalent to) the body of $\mathrm{Pic.pullback}$, together with the functoriality lemmas $\mathrm{Pic.pullback\_id}$ and $\mathrm{Pic.pullback\_comp}$, once the monoidality-iso of the categorical pull-back functor (Theorem~\ref{thm:SheafOfModules_pullback_tensorObj}) is in hand. Post-iter-109, Step~C2 is narrower than its pre-iter-109 framing: the universe bumps cascading out of the Phase~C1 refactor have already been absorbed by the consumers ($\PicardFunctor$ landing in $\mathrm{Type}\,(u+1)$, $\PicardFunctorAb$ landing in $\mathrm{AddCommGrpCat}.\{u+1\}$), so the sorry-bodied declarations remaining downstream of $\Pic$-pullback live in \texttt{Picard/LineBundle.lean} only --- the consumer files \texttt{Picard/Functor.lean} and \texttt{Picard/FunctorAb.lean} compile against the refined $\mathrm{LineBundle}$ without further work. The \'etale-sheafification sub-step has likewise simplified: pre-C1, $\mathrm{PicardFunctorAb.etaleSheafified}$ had to post-compose $\mathrm{AddCommGrpCat.uliftFunctor}_{u+1,u}$ to bridge the universe gap between the iter-004 codomain $\mathrm{AddCommGrpCat}.\{u\}$ and the value-universe $\mathrm{AddCommGrpCat}.\{u+1\}$ at which $\mathrm{HasSheafify}$ is inferable; post-C1, $\PicardFunctorAb$ already lands in $\mathrm{AddCommGrpCat}.\{u+1\}$, so the universe-lift is unnecessary and the body simplifies by one functor composition.
44	    \item \emph{Step~C3} --- construct $\Pic_{C/k}$ (representing scheme) and identify its identity component $\Pic^0_{C/k}$ with $\Jac(C)$. Two routes are viable: (a) the FGA route via a Hilbert/Quot detour (Mathlib-PR-sized); (b) the symmetric-power route via $\mathrm{Sym}^g C$, requiring a project-local quotient-by-finite-group construction. The route is chosen during step~C2.
45	  \end{enumerate}
46	  Until steps~C0--C3 are complete, the Lean-side sorry remains; downstream consumers (Definition~\ref{def:Jacobian} and the four Jacobian instances of Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian}) record their dependence on it through the bundled hypothesis \texttt{nonempty\_jacobianWitness}.
47	\end{proof}
48	
49	\section{Use in the project}
50	
51	Theorem~\ref{thm:Pic_representable} is the bundled blocker for the four Jacobian.lean sorries:
52	
53	\begin{itemize}
54	  \item Definition~\ref{def:Jacobian} ($\Jac(C) = \Pic^0_{C/k}$) takes the connected component of identity of the representing scheme.
55	  \item Theorem~\ref{thm:Jacobian_grpObj} (group-object structure) is the abelian-variety structure on $\Pic^0_{C/k}$.
56	  \item Theorem~\ref{thm:Jacobian_smooth_genus} (smooth of relative dimension $g$) is the dimension formula in the representability statement.
57	  \item Theorem~\ref{thm:Jacobian_proper} (properness) and Theorem~\ref{thm:Jacobian_geomIrred} (geometric irreducibility) are direct consequences of the representability conclusion.
58	\end{itemize}
